owing: Persons with intellectual disabilities claim the right of inspection over public photographic images -- tArt for Transforming Social Care Practice -- tBringing relating to the forefront: Using the art of improvisation to perceive relational processes actively in social work -- tMaking meaning of our experiences of bearing witness to suffering: Employing A/R/Tography to surface co-remembrance and (dwelling) place -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe past two decades have witnessed a vigorous challenge to social work. A growing global convergence between the market and the public sector means that private sector values, priorities, and forms of work organization increasingly permeate social and community services. As challenges facing people and communities become more layered and complex, our means of responding become more time-bound and reductionist. This book is premised on the belief in the revitalizing power of arts-informed approaches to social justice work; it affirms and invites creative responses to personal, community, and political struggles and aspirations. The projects described in the book address themes of colonization, displacement and forced migration, sexual violence, ableism, and vicarious trauma. Each chapter shows how art can facilitate transformation: by supporting processes of conscientization and enabling re-storying of selves and identities; by contributing to community and cultural healing, sustainability and resilience; by helping us understand and challenge oppressive social relations; and by deepening experiences, images, and practices of care. Social Work Artfully: Beyond Borders and Boundaries emerges from collaboration between researchers, educators, and practitioners in Canada and South Africa. It offers examples of arts-informed interventions that are attentive to diversity, attuned to various forms of personal and communal expression, and cognizant of contemporary economic and political conditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArts and societyzCanada. 0aArts and societyzSouth Africa. 0aSocial changezCanada. 0aSocial changezSouth Africa. 0aSocial servicezCanada. 0aSocial servicezSouth Africa. 4aSocial Science: Social Work. 4aSocial Science: Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh  aA/r/tography.  aCanada.  aSouth Africa.  aableism.  aapartheid.  aapplied arts.  aapplied drama.  aapplied theatre.  aarts-informed social work.  acolonization.  aconflict management.  aforced migration.  aimage-making.  aimprovisation.  aindigenous communities.  amanagerialism.  amigrant children.  asexual assault.  asocial justice education.  asocial welfare.  astorytelling.  atrauma.1 aBaines, Donna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnes, Hazel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnes, Hazel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChinyowa, Kennedy C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCross, Nadine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDebassige, Corena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGumede, Khayelihle Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalifax, Nancy Davis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarms Smith, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Randy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaseke, Edwell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKellen, Liebe, econtributor.4ctb4https:/